55// Use to enable experimental gain control (AGC). At startup the experimental
56// AGC moves the microphone volume up to |startup_min_volume| if the current
57// microphone volume is set too low. The value is clamped to its operating range
58// [12, 255]. Here, 255 maps to 100%.
59//
60// Must be provided through AudioProcessingBuilder().Create(config).
61#if defined(WEBRTC_CHROMIUM_BUILD)
62static const int kAgcStartupMinVolume = 85;
63#else
64static const int kAgcStartupMinVolume = 0;
65#endif // defined(WEBRTC_CHROMIUM_BUILD)
66static constexpr int kClippedLevelMin = 70;

69// AudioProcessing::Config::AnalogGainController.

72 ExperimentalAgc() = default;
73 explicit ExperimentalAgc(bool enabled) : enabled(enabled) {}
74 ExperimentalAgc(bool enabled, int startup_min_volume)
75 : enabled(enabled), startup_min_volume(startup_min_volume) {}
76 static const ConfigOptionID identifier = ConfigOptionID::kExperimentalAgc;
77 bool enabled = true;
78 int startup_min_volume = kAgcStartupMinVolume;
79 // Lowest microphone level that will be applied in response to clipping.
80 int clipped_level_min = kClippedLevelMin;
81 bool digital_adaptive_disabled = false;
82};

97// The Audio Processing Module (APM) provides a collection of voice processing
98// components designed for real-time communications software.
99//
100// APM operates on two audio streams on a frame-by-frame basis. Frames of the
101// primary stream, on which all processing is applied, are passed to
102// |ProcessStream()|. Frames of the reverse direction stream are passed to
103// |ProcessReverseStream()|. On the client-side, this will typically be the
104// near-end (capture) and far-end (render) streams, respectively. APM should be
105// placed in the signal chain as close to the audio hardware abstraction layer
106// (HAL) as possible.
107//
108// On the server-side, the reverse stream will normally not be used, with
109// processing occurring on each incoming stream.
110//
111// Component interfaces follow a similar pattern and are accessed through
112// corresponding getters in APM. All components are disabled at create-time,
113// with default settings that are recommended for most situations. New settings
114// can be applied without enabling a component. Enabling a component triggers
115// memory allocation and initialization to allow it to start processing the
116// streams.
117//
118// Thread safety is provided with the following assumptions to reduce locking
119// overhead:
120// 1. The stream getters and setters are called from the same thread as
121// ProcessStream(). More precisely, stream functions are never called
122// concurrently with ProcessStream().
123// 2. Parameter getters are never called concurrently with the corresponding
124// setter.
125//
126// APM accepts only linear PCM audio data in chunks of 10 ms. The int16
127// interfaces use interleaved data, while the float interfaces use deinterleaved
128// data.
129//
130// Usage example, omitting error checking:
131// AudioProcessing* apm = AudioProcessingBuilder().Create();
132//
133// AudioProcessing::Config config;
134// config.echo_canceller.enabled = true;
135// config.echo_canceller.mobile_mode = false;
136//
137// config.gain_controller1.enabled = true;
138// config.gain_controller1.mode =
139// AudioProcessing::Config::GainController1::kAdaptiveAnalog;
140// config.gain_controller1.analog_level_minimum = 0;
141// config.gain_controller1.analog_level_maximum = 255;
142//
143// config.gain_controller2.enabled = true;
144//
145// config.high_pass_filter.enabled = true;
146//
147// config.voice_detection.enabled = true;
148//
149// apm->ApplyConfig(config)
150//
151// apm->noise_reduction()->set_level(kHighSuppression);
152// apm->noise_reduction()->Enable(true);
153//
154// // Start a voice call...
155//
156// // ... Render frame arrives bound for the audio HAL ...
157// apm->ProcessReverseStream(render_frame);
158//
159// // ... Capture frame arrives from the audio HAL ...
160// // Call required set_stream_ functions.
161// apm->set_stream_delay_ms(delay_ms);
162// apm->set_stream_analog_level(analog_level);
163//
164// apm->ProcessStream(capture_frame);
165//
166// // Call required stream_ functions.
167// analog_level = apm->recommended_stream_analog_level();
168// has_voice = apm->stream_has_voice();
169//
170// // Repeat render and capture processing for the duration of the call...
171// // Start a new call...
172// apm->Initialize();
173//
174// // Close the application...
175// delete apm;
176//
177class RTC_EXPORT AudioProcessing : public rtc::RefCountInterface {
178 public:
179 // The struct below constitutes the new parameter scheme for the audio
180 // processing. It is being introduced gradually and until it is fully
181 // introduced, it is prone to change.
182 // TODO(peah): Remove this comment once the new config scheme is fully rolled
183 // out.
184 //
185 // The parameters and behavior of the audio processing module are controlled
186 // by changing the default values in the AudioProcessing::Config struct.
187 // The config is applied by passing the struct to the ApplyConfig method.
188 //
189 // This config is intended to be used during setup, and to enable/disable
190 // top-level processing effects. Use during processing may cause undesired
191 // submodule resets, affecting the audio quality. Use the RuntimeSetting
192 // construct for runtime configuration.
193 struct RTC_EXPORT Config {

200 // Allow multi-channel processing of render audio.
201 bool multi_channel_render = false;
202 // Allow multi-channel processing of capture audio when AEC3 is active
203 // or a custom AEC is injected..
204 bool multi_channel_capture = false;
205 } pipeline;

272 // Enables automatic gain control (AGC) functionality.
273 // The automatic gain control (AGC) component brings the signal to an
274 // appropriate range. This is done by applying a digital gain directly and,
275 // in the analog mode, prescribing an analog gain to be applied at the audio
276 // HAL.
277 // Recommended to be enabled on the client-side.
278 struct RTC_EXPORT GainController1 {
279 bool operator==(const GainController1& rhs) const;
280 bool operator!=(const GainController1& rhs) const {
281 return !(*this == rhs);
282 }
283
284 bool enabled = false;
285 enum Mode {
286 // Adaptive mode intended for use if an analog volume control is
287 // available on the capture device. It will require the user to provide
288 // coupling between the OS mixer controls and AGC through the
289 // stream_analog_level() functions.
290 // It consists of an analog gain prescription for the audio device and a
291 // digital compression stage.
292 kAdaptiveAnalog,
293 // Adaptive mode intended for situations in which an analog volume
294 // control is unavailable. It operates in a similar fashion to the
295 // adaptive analog mode, but with scaling instead applied in the digital
296 // domain. As with the analog mode, it additionally uses a digital
297 // compression stage.
298 kAdaptiveDigital,
299 // Fixed mode which enables only the digital compression stage also used
300 // by the two adaptive modes.
301 // It is distinguished from the adaptive modes by considering only a
302 // short time-window of the input signal. It applies a fixed gain
303 // through most of the input level range, and compresses (gradually
304 // reduces gain with increasing level) the input signal at higher
305 // levels. This mode is preferred on embedded devices where the capture
306 // signal level is predictable, so that a known gain can be applied.
307 kFixedDigital
308 };
309 Mode mode = kAdaptiveAnalog;
310 // Sets the target peak level (or envelope) of the AGC in dBFs (decibels
311 // from digital full-scale). The convention is to use positive values. For
312 // instance, passing in a value of 3 corresponds to -3 dBFs, or a target
313 // level 3 dB below full-scale. Limited to [0, 31].
314 int target_level_dbfs = 3;
315 // Sets the maximum gain the digital compression stage may apply, in dB. A
316 // higher number corresponds to greater compression, while a value of 0
317 // will leave the signal uncompressed. Limited to [0, 90].
318 // For updates after APM setup, use a RuntimeSetting instead.
319 int compression_gain_db = 9;
320 // When enabled, the compression stage will hard limit the signal to the
321 // target level. Otherwise, the signal will be compressed but not limited
322 // above the target level.
323 bool enable_limiter = true;
324 // Sets the minimum and maximum analog levels of the audio capture device.
325 // Must be set if an analog mode is used. Limited to [0, 65535].
326 int analog_level_minimum = 0;
327 int analog_level_maximum = 255;

340 // Enables the next generation AGC functionality. This feature replaces the
341 // standard methods of gain control in the previous AGC. Enabling this
342 // submodule enables an adaptive digital AGC followed by a limiter. By
343 // setting |fixed_gain_db|, the limiter can be turned into a compressor that

345 // setting |adaptive_digital_mode=false|.

348 bool operator!=(const GainController2& rhs) const {
349 return !(*this == rhs);

410 // Specifies the properties of a setting to be passed to AudioProcessing at
411 // runtime.
412 class RuntimeSetting {
413 public:
414 enum class Type {
415 kNotSpecified,
416 kCapturePreGain,
417 kCaptureCompressionGain,
418 kCaptureFixedPostGain,
419 kPlayoutVolumeChange,
420 kCustomRenderProcessingRuntimeSetting,
421 kPlayoutAudioDeviceChange,
422 kCapturePostGain,
423 kCaptureOutputUsed
424 };
425
426 // Play-out audio device properties.
427 struct PlayoutAudioDeviceInfo {
428 int id; // Identifies the audio device.
429 int max_volume; // Maximum play-out volume.
430 };
431
432 RuntimeSetting() : type_(Type::kNotSpecified), value_(0.0f) {}
433 ~RuntimeSetting() = default;
434
435 static RuntimeSetting CreateCapturePreGain(float gain) {
436 return {Type::kCapturePreGain, gain};
437 }
438
439 static RuntimeSetting CreateCapturePostGain(float gain) {
440 return {Type::kCapturePostGain, gain};
441 }
442
443 // Corresponds to Config::GainController1::compression_gain_db, but for
444 // runtime configuration.
445 static RuntimeSetting CreateCompressionGainDb(int gain_db) {
446 RTC_DCHECK_GE(gain_db, 0);
447 RTC_DCHECK_LE(gain_db, 90);
448 return {Type::kCaptureCompressionGain, static_cast<float>(gain_db)};
449 }
450
451 // Corresponds to Config::GainController2::fixed_digital::gain_db, but for
452 // runtime configuration.
453 static RuntimeSetting CreateCaptureFixedPostGain(float gain_db) {
454 RTC_DCHECK_GE(gain_db, 0.0f);
455 RTC_DCHECK_LE(gain_db, 90.0f);
456 return {Type::kCaptureFixedPostGain, gain_db};
457 }
458
459 // Creates a runtime setting to notify play-out (aka render) audio device
460 // changes.
461 static RuntimeSetting CreatePlayoutAudioDeviceChange(
462 PlayoutAudioDeviceInfo audio_device) {
463 return {Type::kPlayoutAudioDeviceChange, audio_device};
464 }
465
466 // Creates a runtime setting to notify play-out (aka render) volume changes.
467 // |volume| is the unnormalized volume, the maximum of which
468 static RuntimeSetting CreatePlayoutVolumeChange(int volume) {
469 return {Type::kPlayoutVolumeChange, volume};
470 }
471
472 static RuntimeSetting CreateCustomRenderSetting(float payload) {
473 return {Type::kCustomRenderProcessingRuntimeSetting, payload};
474 }
475
476 static RuntimeSetting CreateCaptureOutputUsedSetting(
477 bool capture_output_used) {
478 return {Type::kCaptureOutputUsed, capture_output_used};
479 }
480
481 Type type() const { return type_; }
482 // Getters do not return a value but instead modify the argument to protect
483 // from implicit casting.
484 void GetFloat(float* value) const {
485 RTC_DCHECK(value);
486 *value = value_.float_value;
487 }
488 void GetInt(int* value) const {
489 RTC_DCHECK(value);
490 *value = value_.int_value;
491 }
492 void GetBool(bool* value) const {
493 RTC_DCHECK(value);
494 *value = value_.bool_value;
495 }
496 void GetPlayoutAudioDeviceInfo(PlayoutAudioDeviceInfo* value) const {
497 RTC_DCHECK(value);
498 *value = value_.playout_audio_device_info;
499 }
500
501 private:
502 RuntimeSetting(Type id, float value) : type_(id), value_(value) {}
503 RuntimeSetting(Type id, int value) : type_(id), value_(value) {}
504 RuntimeSetting(Type id, PlayoutAudioDeviceInfo value)
505 : type_(id), value_(value) {}
506 Type type_;
507 union U {
508 U() {}
509 U(int value) : int_value(value) {}
510 U(float value) : float_value(value) {}
511 U(PlayoutAudioDeviceInfo value) : playout_audio_device_info(value) {}
512 float float_value;
513 int int_value;
514 bool bool_value;
515 PlayoutAudioDeviceInfo playout_audio_device_info;
516 } value_;
517 };

521 // Initializes internal states, while retaining all user settings. This
522 // should be called before beginning to process a new audio stream. However,
523 // it is not necessary to call before processing the first stream after
524 // creation.
525 //
526 // It is also not necessary to call if the audio parameters (sample
527 // rate and number of channels) have changed. Passing updated parameters
528 // directly to |ProcessStream()| and |ProcessReverseStream()| is permissible.
529 // If the parameters are known at init-time though, they may be provided.
530 // TODO(webrtc:5298): Change to return void.
531 virtual int Initialize() = 0;
532
533 // The int16 interfaces require:
534 // - only |NativeRate|s be used
535 // - that the input, output and reverse rates must match
536 // - that |processing_config.output_stream()| matches
537 // |processing_config.input_stream()|.
538 //
539 // The float interfaces accept arbitrary rates and support differing input and
540 // output layouts, but the output must have either one channel or the same
541 // number of channels as the input.
542 virtual int Initialize(const ProcessingConfig& processing_config) = 0;
543
544 // Initialize with unpacked parameters. See Initialize() above for details.
545 //
546 // TODO(mgraczyk): Remove once clients are updated to use the new interface.
547 virtual int Initialize(int capture_input_sample_rate_hz,
548 int capture_output_sample_rate_hz,
549 int render_sample_rate_hz,
550 ChannelLayout capture_input_layout,
551 ChannelLayout capture_output_layout,
552 ChannelLayout render_input_layout) = 0;
553
554 // TODO(peah): This method is a temporary solution used to take control
555 // over the parameters in the audio processing module and is likely to change.
556 virtual void ApplyConfig(const Config& config) = 0;
557
558 // TODO(ajm): Only intended for internal use. Make private and friend the
559 // necessary classes?
560 virtual int proc_sample_rate_hz() const = 0;
561 virtual int proc_split_sample_rate_hz() const = 0;
562 virtual size_t num_input_channels() const = 0;
563 virtual size_t num_proc_channels() const = 0;
564 virtual size_t num_output_channels() const = 0;
565 virtual size_t num_reverse_channels() const = 0;

567 // Set to true when the output of AudioProcessing will be muted or in some
568 // other way not used. Ideally, the captured audio would still be processed,
569 // but some components may change behavior based on this information.
570 // Default false. This method takes a lock. To achieve this in a lock-less
571 // manner the PostRuntimeSetting can instead be used.
572 virtual void set_output_will_be_muted(bool muted) = 0;
573
574 // Enqueues a runtime setting.
575 virtual void SetRuntimeSetting(RuntimeSetting setting) = 0;
576
577 // Enqueues a runtime setting. Returns a bool indicating whether the
578 // enqueueing was successfull.
579 virtual bool PostRuntimeSetting(RuntimeSetting setting) = 0;

581 // Accepts and produces a 10 ms frame interleaved 16 bit integer audio as
582 // specified in |input_config| and |output_config|. |src| and |dest| may use
583 // the same memory, if desired.
584 virtual int ProcessStream(const int16_t* const src,
585 const StreamConfig& input_config,
586 const StreamConfig& output_config,
587 int16_t* const dest) = 0;
588
589 // Accepts deinterleaved float audio with the range [-1, 1]. Each element of
590 // |src| points to a channel buffer, arranged according to |input_stream|. At
591 // output, the channels will be arranged according to |output_stream| in
592 // |dest|.
593 //
594 // The output must have one channel or as many channels as the input. |src|
595 // and |dest| may use the same memory, if desired.
596 virtual int ProcessStream(const float* const* src,
597 const StreamConfig& input_config,
598 const StreamConfig& output_config,
599 float* const* dest) = 0;
600
601 // Accepts and produces a 10 ms frame of interleaved 16 bit integer audio for
602 // the reverse direction audio stream as specified in |input_config| and
603 // |output_config|. |src| and |dest| may use the same memory, if desired.
604 virtual int ProcessReverseStream(const int16_t* const src,
605 const StreamConfig& input_config,
606 const StreamConfig& output_config,
607 int16_t* const dest) = 0;
608
609 // Accepts deinterleaved float audio with the range [-1, 1]. Each element of
610 // |data| points to a channel buffer, arranged according to |reverse_config|.
611 virtual int ProcessReverseStream(const float* const* src,
612 const StreamConfig& input_config,
613 const StreamConfig& output_config,
614 float* const* dest) = 0;
615
616 // Accepts deinterleaved float audio with the range [-1, 1]. Each element
617 // of |data| points to a channel buffer, arranged according to
618 // |reverse_config|.
619 virtual int AnalyzeReverseStream(const float* const* data,
620 const StreamConfig& reverse_config) = 0;
621
622 // Returns the most recently produced 10 ms of the linear AEC output at a rate
623 // of 16 kHz. If there is more than one capture channel, a mono representation
624 // of the input is returned. Returns true/false to indicate whether an output
625 // returned.
626 virtual bool GetLinearAecOutput(
627 rtc::ArrayView<std::array<float, 160>> linear_output) const = 0;
628
629 // This must be called prior to ProcessStream() if and only if adaptive analog
630 // gain control is enabled, to pass the current analog level from the audio
631 // HAL. Must be within the range provided in Config::GainController1.
632 virtual void set_stream_analog_level(int level) = 0;
633
634 // When an analog mode is set, this should be called after ProcessStream()
635 // to obtain the recommended new analog level for the audio HAL. It is the
636 // user's responsibility to apply this level.
637 virtual int recommended_stream_analog_level() const = 0;
638
639 // This must be called if and only if echo processing is enabled.
640 //
641 // Sets the |delay| in ms between ProcessReverseStream() receiving a far-end
642 // frame and ProcessStream() receiving a near-end frame containing the
643 // corresponding echo. On the client-side this can be expressed as
644 // delay = (t_render - t_analyze) + (t_process - t_capture)
645 // where,
646 // - t_analyze is the time a frame is passed to ProcessReverseStream() and
647 // t_render is the time the first sample of the same frame is rendered by
648 // the audio hardware.
649 // - t_capture is the time the first sample of a frame is captured by the
650 // audio hardware and t_process is the time the same frame is passed to
651 // ProcessStream().
652 virtual int set_stream_delay_ms(int delay) = 0;
653 virtual int stream_delay_ms() const = 0;
654
655 // Call to signal that a key press occurred (true) or did not occur (false)
656 // with this chunk of audio.
657 virtual void set_stream_key_pressed(bool key_pressed) = 0;

659 // Creates and attaches an webrtc::AecDump for recording debugging
660 // information.
661 // The |worker_queue| may not be null and must outlive the created
662 // AecDump instance. |max_log_size_bytes == -1| means the log size
663 // will be unlimited. |handle| may not be null. The AecDump takes
664 // responsibility for |handle| and closes it in the destructor. A
665 // return value of true indicates that the file has been
666 // sucessfully opened, while a value of false indicates that
667 // opening the file failed.
668 virtual bool CreateAndAttachAecDump(const std::string& file_name,
669 int64_t max_log_size_bytes,
670 rtc::TaskQueue* worker_queue) = 0;
671 virtual bool CreateAndAttachAecDump(FILE* handle,
672 int64_t max_log_size_bytes,
673 rtc::TaskQueue* worker_queue) = 0;

675 // TODO(webrtc:5298) Deprecated variant.
676 // Attaches provided webrtc::AecDump for recording debugging
677 // information. Log file and maximum file size logic is supposed to
678 // be handled by implementing instance of AecDump. Calling this
679 // method when another AecDump is attached resets the active AecDump
680 // with a new one. This causes the d-tor of the earlier AecDump to
681 // be called. The d-tor call may block until all pending logging
682 // tasks are completed.
683 virtual void AttachAecDump(std::unique_ptr<AecDump> aec_dump) = 0;
684
685 // If no AecDump is attached, this has no effect. If an AecDump is
686 // attached, it's destructor is called. The d-tor may block until
687 // all pending logging tasks are completed.
688 virtual void DetachAecDump() = 0;
689
690 // Get audio processing statistics.
691 virtual AudioProcessingStats GetStatistics() = 0;
692 // TODO(webrtc:5298) Deprecated variant. The |has_remote_tracks| argument
693 // should be set if there are active remote tracks (this would usually be true
694 // during a call). If there are no remote tracks some of the stats will not be
695 // set by AudioProcessing, because they only make sense if there is at least
696 // one remote track.
697 virtual AudioProcessingStats GetStatistics(bool has_remote_tracks) = 0;

724 // Native rates supported by the integer interfaces.
725 enum NativeRate {
726 kSampleRate8kHz = 8000,
727 kSampleRate16kHz = 16000,
728 kSampleRate32kHz = 32000,
729 kSampleRate48kHz = 48000
730 };
731
732 // TODO(kwiberg): We currently need to support a compiler (Visual C++) that
733 // complains if we don't explicitly state the size of the array here. Remove
734 // the size when that's no longer the case.
735 static constexpr int kNativeSampleRatesHz[4] = {
736 kSampleRate8kHz, kSampleRate16kHz, kSampleRate32kHz, kSampleRate48kHz};
737 static constexpr size_t kNumNativeSampleRates =
738 arraysize(kNativeSampleRatesHz);
739 static constexpr int kMaxNativeSampleRateHz =
740 kNativeSampleRatesHz[kNumNativeSampleRates - 1];
741
742 static constexpr int kChunkSizeMs = 10;
743};

793class StreamConfig {
794 public:
795 // sample_rate_hz: The sampling rate of the stream.
796 //
797 // num_channels: The number of audio channels in the stream, excluding the
798 // keyboard channel if it is present. When passing a
799 // StreamConfig with an array of arrays T*[N],
800 //
801 // N == {num_channels + 1 if has_keyboard
802 // {num_channels if !has_keyboard
803 //
804 // has_keyboard: True if the stream has a keyboard channel. When has_keyboard
805 // is true, the last channel in any corresponding list of
806 // channels is the keyboard channel.
807 StreamConfig(int sample_rate_hz = 0,
808 size_t num_channels = 0,
809 bool has_keyboard = false)
810 : sample_rate_hz_(sample_rate_hz),
811 num_channels_(num_channels),
812 has_keyboard_(has_keyboard),
813 num_frames_(calculate_frames(sample_rate_hz)) {}
814
815 void set_sample_rate_hz(int value) {
816 sample_rate_hz_ = value;
817 num_frames_ = calculate_frames(value);
818 }
819 void set_num_channels(size_t value) { num_channels_ = value; }
820 void set_has_keyboard(bool value) { has_keyboard_ = value; }
821
822 int sample_rate_hz() const { return sample_rate_hz_; }
823
824 // The number of channels in the stream, not including the keyboard channel if
825 // present.
826 size_t num_channels() const { return num_channels_; }
827
828 bool has_keyboard() const { return has_keyboard_; }
829 size_t num_frames() const { return num_frames_; }
830 size_t num_samples() const { return num_channels_ * num_frames_; }
831
832 bool operator==(const StreamConfig& other) const {
833 return sample_rate_hz_ == other.sample_rate_hz_ &&
834 num_channels_ == other.num_channels_ &&
835 has_keyboard_ == other.has_keyboard_;
836 }
837
838 bool operator!=(const StreamConfig& other) const { return !(*this == other); }
839
840 private:
841 static size_t calculate_frames(int sample_rate_hz) {
842 return static_cast<size_t>(AudioProcessing::kChunkSizeMs * sample_rate_hz /
843 1000);
844 }
845
846 int sample_rate_hz_;
847 size_t num_channels_;
848 bool has_keyboard_;
849 size_t num_frames_;
850};

852class ProcessingConfig {
853 public:
854 enum StreamName {
855 kInputStream,
856 kOutputStream,
857 kReverseInputStream,
858 kReverseOutputStream,
859 kNumStreamNames,
860 };
861
862 const StreamConfig& input_stream() const {
863 return streams[StreamName::kInputStream];
864 }
865 const StreamConfig& output_stream() const {
866 return streams[StreamName::kOutputStream];
867 }
868 const StreamConfig& reverse_input_stream() const {
869 return streams[StreamName::kReverseInputStream];
870 }
871 const StreamConfig& reverse_output_stream() const {
872 return streams[StreamName::kReverseOutputStream];
873 }
874
875 StreamConfig& input_stream() { return streams[StreamName::kInputStream]; }
876 StreamConfig& output_stream() { return streams[StreamName::kOutputStream]; }
877 StreamConfig& reverse_input_stream() {
878 return streams[StreamName::kReverseInputStream];
879 }
880 StreamConfig& reverse_output_stream() {
881 return streams[StreamName::kReverseOutputStream];
882 }
883
884 bool operator==(const ProcessingConfig& other) const {
885 for (int i = 0; i < StreamName::kNumStreamNames; ++i) {
886 if (this->streams[i] != other.streams[i]) {
887 return false;
888 }
889 }
890 return true;
891 }
892
893 bool operator!=(const ProcessingConfig& other) const {
894 return !(*this == other);
895 }
896
897 StreamConfig streams[StreamName::kNumStreamNames];
898};
